SUMMARIZER="G">     

A Northwest Airlines jet crashed Sunday in Detroit, killing at least
154 people.  Engine failure appeared to be the culprit, but FAA
officials would not speculate on the reasons for the crash saying it
was too early to draw firm conclusions. Following a summer of snafus,
the accident could be a catalyst for reassessing the Nation's
air-travel system.  All jetliners must be capable of take-off ascent,
even if one engine fails, if the aircraft is within prescribed weight
limits.  The plane had a large fuel load and was jammed with
passengers.  Congress is expected to act on aviation bills this
fall.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d59"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880517-0226"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="G">  

A single-engine airplane crashed Tuesday on the outskirts of
Albuquerque while trying to land at nearby Coronado Airport.  All five
people aboard were killed.  Identities of the victims were not
immediately available.  A witness reported the plane was having
difficulty attempting a landing because of high winds and sprinkling
rain.  A gust of wind hit the plane as it was banking and caused it to
crash nose first into the ground.  Witnesses went to the crash site
but retreated when it appeared to plane might blow up.  Authorities
are in route to the crash site to conduct an investigation.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d59"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881222-0089"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="G">  

A Pan Am Boeing 747 apparently exploded in the air 54 minutes after
takeoff from London's Heathrow Airport.  The wreckage scattered bodies
and debris over 10 miles of countryside and ravaged the village of
Lockerbie, Scotland.  All 259 people aboard the plan and 22 on the
ground were killed.  Sabotage is believed to be the most likely
explanation for the crash.  An anonymous caller to the AP office in
London claimed responsibility for the crash saying it was retaliation
by the "Guardians of the Islamic Revolution" for the downing of an
Iran Air Airbus by a US cruiser in July.</SUM>


<SUM
