TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA092189-0123"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="G">  

A French DC-10 jetliner with 171 people aboard blew up at high
altitude before crashing in a desert region of Niger.  There is
speculation that the jetliner was bombed by terrorists in retaliation
against France for sending a naval task force into Lebanese waters to
rescue French nationals in war-torn Lebanon.  Many perceived the
action as support for Maronite Christian forces against Syrian troops
and Muslim militia in Lebanon.  Several militant groups threatened
attacks against France in August.  The states of Iran and Libya are
under suspicion.  Seven Americans, including the wife of the US
Ambassador to Chad, were aboard the plane.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d59"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890111-0217"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="G">  

Authorities questioned the injured pilot of a Boeing 737 which crashed
short of the runway at East Midlands Airport in England, but revealed
no clues as to why the jet's undamaged right engine was shut down
while the other engine burned.  The government ordered checks of
engine monitoring systems, prompting speculation that a malfunctioning
alarm system could have misled the crew.  The plane's CFM56 engines
have parts manufactured by a General Electric Company, which may have
falsified its test records.  Boeing said aircraft that use the engine
are being inspected, but it does not imply a cause has been
identified.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d59"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910304-0005"
SELECTOR="K"
SUMMARIZER="G">  

A United Airlines Boeing 737 jetliner crashed nose down near Colorado
Springs, CO, Municipal Airport, apparently killing all 25 persons
aboard.  There were no early indications on why the jet crashed.  One
focus is on whether there were unstable winds strong enough to cause
wind shear, a sudden, violent shift in wind direction that can smash
an airplane into the ground.  However, it is most dangerous when an
aircraft is at low altitudes such as shortly before landing or just
after takeoff.  When the jetliner crashed, it was a few miles from the
airport and thus at higher altitude.</SUM>
